explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Need the macro expansion/signature to know whether it yields a pointer to a mutable record or a pointer-to-const. If it returns a const pointer, passing &impl->cv would produce a const-qualified pointer and violate the pthread API usage; if it returns non-const, the current code may be acceptable.
OS_impl_condvar_table: The declaration/type of the table (array/structure) is required because OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET typically indexes/returns from this table; its element type and const-qualification determine whether the returned record is const.
OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t: The struct definition is required to see the declarations of members 'cv' and 'mut' (their types and any const qualifiers). The constness of the record or its members affects whether &impl->cv and &impl->mut produce pointers to const-qualified types.
OS_object_token_t: The typedef/definition is needed to know what *token yields (an index/id type or something else) and whether taking it from 'const OS_object_token_t *token' could force a const-qualified access into the table.
pthread_cond_destroy: Prototype is needed to confirm the function signature takes 'pthread_cond_t *' (non-const) and therefore requires a non-const pointer argument; this is central to deciding if impl must be non-const.
pthread_mutex_destroy: Prototype is needed for the same reason as pthread_cond_destroy (it takes 'pthread_mutex_t *' non-const).
pthread_cond_t and pthread_mutex_t: The concrete types of these members (as used in the impl struct) are needed to confirm the exact types and how const qualification on the containing record propagates to the pointer types passed to the destroy functions.
